  "chunk_index": 37,
  "summary": "Anthony examines a scrap of paper containing an address, which Lemont claims he has never seen before. Lemont suggests the paper may have fallen from Essex's suitcase and advises Anthony to investigate Pourezzi, a servant of Michael Prince, noting that Victor could be impersonating a servant. Lemont expresses that his primary preoccupation is capturing Victor King, stating his purpose in England is to find him rather than to solve the diamond theft or Prince's murder. Anthony observes that Lemont has already recorded the address on his shirt cuff.\n\nLater, Anthony speaks with Chief Constable Bartlett, who is troubled by the lack of clarity in the investigation. Bartlett reveals he received an anonymous, misspelled note warning that Anthony is \"not what he sees.\" Anthony dismisses the note and returns to the villa, where he becomes solemn and decides he must act. He heads to the rose garden and encounters Mr. Fuchs. After a polite conversation regarding rose varieties, Bunder invites Mr. Fuchs to drive to London.\n\nAs Bunder's car departs, Anthony suddenly changes his demeanor and races through the courtyard to intercept the vehicle. He vaults over a wall and jumps into the passenger seat of Bunder's Panhard, announcing his intention to go to London. Bunder notices Anthony is holding a match, which he pockets after examining it. As they drive at high speeds through the countryside, Bunder questions Anthony's sudden departure and whether he is escaping the law, musing that the Scotland Yard man is not as weak as expected.",
